mathew@mantis.co.uk (mathew) writes:

>In article <Mar.18.14.52.05.1994.22344@pilot.njin.net>,
>Sean Casey <csc@pilot.njin.net> wrote:
>>I don't know why otherwise clueful people (like a certain Wired
>>employee I know) will make this argument. People don't type random
>>characters in their passwords or passphrases. As "crack" so elegantly
>>shows, one can substantially reduce the keyspace searched, even more
>>so if any information can be gathered on the user.

>The assumption is that anyone who is concerned enough about privacy
>and security to set up and use an encrypting filesystem will not be
>the kind of stupid twonk who uses dictionary words as passwords and
>picks a short enough passphrase that it matters.

SFS in fact includes a few simple safeguards to make sure you don't enter 
something like a single dictionary word as your passphrase (try doing it 
when mksfs asks you for a password).  It's not bulletproof, but it should be 
enough to point people in the right direction.
 
Peter.
